  "summary": "Colonel Melrose interrogates the footman, Jenkins, regarding his movements during the time of the murder. Jenkins explains that he brought soft leather slippers to his master and took away a pair of brogues, leaving the study after 6:15 and returning to the servants' quarters by 6:30. Inspector Curtis confirms that Jenkins was in the servants' room from approximately 6:20 to 7:00, effectively clearing him of suspicion.\n\nAn anxious maid then announces that Laura DeWitt wishes to see the Colonel. Appearing unsteady in a navy blue brocade tea gown, Laura is led into a sitting room where she suddenly confesses to shooting Sir James de Witt downstairs. When Mr. Quincannon asks about the murder weapon, Laura becomes agitated, claiming she cannot remember clearly if she dropped the pistol or threw it out a window. As she departs, the maid expresses concern that Jenkins might be suspected of the crime.\n\nFollowing Laura's departure, a man named Paul Danglars arrives with an elegant, theatrical bearing. Danglars confesses to the murder, claiming he stabbed Sir James in the heart with a gem-encrusted paper knife taken from Lady DeWitt's book. He states that he entered and exited through a window around 6:30, after having chatted with the gamekeeper at 6:15. Colonel Melrose informs the stunned Danglars that Mrs. DeWitt has also already come forward with a confession.",
